<p>You can view and copy the source of this page:
</p><textarea readonly="" accesskey="," id="wpTextbox1" cols="80" rows="25" style="" lang="en" dir="ltr" name="wpTextbox1">[[File:android_app_architecture.png|400px|thumb|right|Architecture for the Android Tecla input method. The Switch Event Provider is a service that receives switch events via bluetooth from the Tecla Access Shield and broadcasts them to the OS.]]

The [http://scyp.idrc.ocad.ca/projects/tekla/the-app Tecla Access App for Android] has two main software components:

* The Tecla Input Method (Tecla IME) and,
* the [[Tecla_Access/Switch_Event_Provider|Switch Event Provider (SEP)]]

== Tecla Input Method ==

===Features===
* Acts as a standard soft keyboard when no accessibility options are selected
* Receives switch event broadcast (intents) from the [[Tecla_Access/Switch_Event_Provider|Switch Event Provider (SEP)]] and uses them to navigate, select and forward key events (D-pad, hardware buttons, keyboard) to the OS via scanning.

=== ToDo ===
* Provide container for alternative access methods (e.g. Morse).

===Implementation Notes===

Important notes on implementation are included here. For a list of implementation requirements and details on the alternatives explored visit the [[Talk:Tecla_Access/App|discussion page]].

==== Explicitly hiding/showing the soft input method ====

The IME Service class offers the following methods:

&lt;pre>
showWindow(boolean force)
hideWindow()
&lt;/pre>

Although these methods are not well documented, we managed to use them to achieve our goals. the &lt;code>force&lt;/code> boolean in the first method seems to be the difference between a request and a forced action.

==== Highlighting ====

This was done by manipulating the &lt;code>pressed&lt;/code> property of key objects in the Tecla IME. A drawable was used to implement the background color change.

==== Sending Individual Keys to an Application ====

A method was created to emulate hardware key events, the following example sends a DPAD UP key to an application:
&lt;pre>
getCurrentInputConnection().sendKeyEvent(new KeyEvent(KeyEvent.ACTION_DOWN, KeyEvent.KEYCODE_DPAD_UP));
getCurrentInputConnection().sendKeyEvent(new KeyEvent(KeyEvent.ACTION_UP, KeyEvent.KEYCODE_DPAD_UP));
&lt;/pre>
However, these events cannot send key events to overlays such as the application's options menu and some pop-ups. There are still no known solutions for [https://bugs.launchpad.net/meadl/+bug/617060 this issue].
</textarea><div class="templatesUsed"></div><p id="mw-returnto">Return to <a href="/Tecla_Access/App" title="Tecla Access/App">Tecla Access/App</a>.</p>
